‚ü¶ Typed FFI Example: List Length from fs.readdir

  This demonstrates the key benefit of typed FFI: when fs‚ãÖpromises.readdir
  has a type signature that returns [String], we can use the # operator on the result.

  With untyped FFI (trust mode), fs‚ãÖpromises.readdir returns type 'any',
  and # operator fails because you can't apply # to type any.
‚üß

‚ü¶ Typed FFI declaration: readdir returns [String], not any ‚üß
e fs‚ãÖpromises : {
  readdir : Œª(String) ‚Üí [String]
}

‚ü¶ Count files in a directory ‚üß
ŒªcountFiles(dir:String)‚ÜíInt={
  l files=(fs‚ãÖpromises.readdir(dir):[String]);
  #files  ‚ü¶ Works! files has type [String], not any ‚üß
}

‚ü¶ Main entry point ‚üß
Œªmain()‚ÜíInt={
  countFiles(".")
}
